# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/1812-in-literature] This article contains information about the literary events and publications of **1812**.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] "**A Defence of Poetry**" is an unfinished essay by Percy Bysshe Shelley written in February and March 1821 that the poet put aside and never completed.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] In 1840, the text was published posthumously in *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Its earliest U.S. publication was by Ginn and Company in Boston in 1891.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley wrote the essay in response to his friend Thomas Love Peacock's article "The Four Ages of Poetry", which had been published in 1820.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] , I mean to set about an answer to it....
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] It is very clever, but I think, very false.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Your anathemas against poetry itself excited me to a sacred rage. . . .
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] The text we know as *A Defence of Poetry* was eventually published eighteen years after Shelley's death, after being subjected to some editing by John Hunt and Shelley's wife Mary Shelley, in her *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's aim was to show that poets establish morality and inspire the legal norms in a civil society, thus creating a foundation for the other institutions of a community.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] , [Shelley] attempts to prove that poets are philosophers; that they are the creators and protectors of moral and civil laws; and that if it were not for poets, scientists could not have developed either their theories or their inventions.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] The mores so created are codified into laws.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] The social function or utility of poets is that they create and maintain the norms and mores of a society.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] ...Shelley was mainly concerned to explain the moral (and thus the social) function of poetry.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] In doing so, he produced one of the most penetrating general discussions on poetry that we have.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley’s argument for poetry is an important text of English Romanticism.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's conclusive remark that "Poets are the unacknowledged legislators of the world" suggests his awareness of "the profound ambiguity inherent in linguistic means, which he considers at once as an instrument of intellectual freedom and a vehicle for political and social subjugation".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] "**A Dirge**" is a poetic dirge composed by Percy Bysshe Shelley.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] It was published posthumously in 1824 by his wife, Mary Shelley, in the collection *Posthumous Poems*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The text has been set to music by Frank Bridge, Charles Ives, Ottorino Respighi, Roy Ewing Agnew, and Benjamin Britten.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The rhyme scheme of the eight lines is ABAB CCCB.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The triplet of vain/strain/main in the second half of the poem adds to the sense of the piling up of emotions.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] It also has the effect of slowing down the poem.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The dominant themes of the poem are isolation, loneliness, and death.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] It is a scene of desolation and despair.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The wind moans in a grief that cannot be expressed in words; the rain storm billows in vain; the trees are barren and their branches strain under the unceasing onslaught.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] A dirge is a song meant to invoke and express the emotions of grief and mourning that are typical of a funeral.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] Images of nature are used to symbolize the grief he feels, such as the moaning and wild wind, the sullen clouds, the sad storm, the bare woods, the deep caves, and the dreary main.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] He imbues his natural surroundings with anthropomorphic characteristics and qualities to express his grief.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The nouns are modified by adjectives that give them human attributes and traits to express his own emotions of dreariness and sadness.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] He concludes that the whole world is “wrong” and is grieving.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] Shelley wrote the poem after the deaths of his friend John Keats and his son William who were buried in a cemetery in Rome.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The untimely death of Keats reopened the floodgates of emotion for Shelley, inevitably leading him to reexperience the sadness and pain he felt for the death of his infant son.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] In the second line, “Grief too sad for song,” Shelley argued that the grief was ineffable, inexpressible in words.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] The last line, “Wail, for the world’s wrong!”, provides a sense of hope and consolation.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-dirge] Rough wind, that moanest loud Grief too sad for song; Wild wind, when sullen cloud Knells all the night long; Sad storm whose tears are vain, Bare woods, whose branches strain, Deep caves and dreary main,— Wail, for the world's wrong!
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] "**A Letter to Lord Ellenborough**" is a pamphlet written in 1812 by Percy Bysshe Shelley in defence of Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Printed in Barnstaple, the essay is approximately 4,000 words in length.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley defended freedom of speech and criticized the sentencing of publisher Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley argued against punishing blasphemous libel maintaining that religious belief is involuntary and that opinions, even if false, should not be prosecuted.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the essay, Shelley argues for concepts which were then quite radical, including complete freedom of the press, and a tolerance for all published opinion, even when false.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The epigraph on the title page is by Tacitus from *The Annals*, Deorum Offensa, Diis curae.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] An offense to the gods is rectified by the gods.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] A speech by the Marquess Wellesley from July 2 in the *Globe* is quoted.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the Advertisement, Shelley wrote that he had waited for four months for someone to attack the sentence but when none was forthcoming, he wrote the letter.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The title arises from the name of the letter's recipient, who directed the jury that convicted Eaton.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton had been tried and found guilty of "blasphemous libel", for being an atheist.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] At the trial before Edward Law, 1st Baron Ellenborough, the Lord Chief Justice of England, what Mark Sandy of the University of Durham has called a "prejudiced jury" convicted Eaton for printing part three of Thomas Paine's *The Age of Reason*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Daniel Eaton was put on trial in May 1812.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] During the trial, in which he was accused of being an atheist, as well as the aforementioned "blasphemous libel." In defending himself, Eaton claimed that his beliefs were not atheistic, but deistic.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] He attempted to argue that scripture was open to the type of critique that Thomas Paine had leveled in *The Age of Reason*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Despite the paucity of evidence, on 15 May 1812, the Ellenborough-led jury found Eaton guilty.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] His sentence was severe, including eighteen months in Newgate Prison and a monthly pillorying for the entire term of his sentence.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was originally printed in 1812 in Barnstaple by W.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Syle, but because they anticipated prosecution, the edition was mostly destroyed, with only 50 copies delivered to London for private distribution.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was published in book form in 1859 in the *Shelley Memorials*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was included in *The Prose Works of Percy Bysshe Shelley*, Volume 1, edited by Harry Buxton Forman in 1880, published by Reeves and Turner in London.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished as *Shelley on Blasphemy: Being His Letter to Lord Ellenborough, Occasioned by the Sentence which He Passed on Mr.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton* in 1883 in London by the Progressive Publishing Company.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished in *A letter to Lord Ellenborough: Occasioned by the Sentence Which He Passed on Mr.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton as publisher of the third part of Paine's 'Age of Reason'* in 1894 in London by R.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley composed *A Philosophical View of Reform* between November, 1819 and 20 May 1820, meant to address political developments in England at that time.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He advocated non-violence and a moderate response to the repressive measures imposed by the British government.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] One of the events he addressed was the Peterloo Massacre, which occurred on 16 August 1819, in St.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Peter's Field near Manchester, where a peaceful demonstration seeking parliamentary reform was attacked by militia.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The bookseller Richard Carlile had been found guilty of blasphemy by a jury in November, 1819 for printing an edition of *The Age of Reason* (1794-6) by Thomas Paine.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The “Six Acts” had been promulgated in December which placed restrictions on public gatherings and freedom of the press.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] It was during this unstable political period in England in late 1819 when Shelley started writing *A Philosophical View of Reform*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 4. abolish tithes, and make all religions, all forms of opinion regarding the origin and government of the universe, equal under the law.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 5. make justice inexpensive, certain, and speedy, and extend the institution of juries to every possible occasion of jurisprudence.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley opposed revolution, advocating instead gradual change through non-violence.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He argued that individual and institutional reform went hand in hand.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He maintained that poets, writers, and philosophers would stimulate reforms of the social institutions that would benefit everyone in society.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley informed his publisher Charles Ollier on 19 December 1819 that he sought *A Philosophical View of Reform* "to be an instructive and readable book, appealing from the passions to the reason of men", informing him that he would not finish it "this season".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] On 26 May 1820 he asked Leigh Hunt if he could find a publisher for the work: "Do you know any bookseller who wd publish for me an octavo volume entitled 'A philosophical View of Reform'.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Mary Shelley had a transcript made of the manuscript with plans to publish the work.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The political essay remained unpublished, however, until 1920 when it appeared for the first time in print in an edition published by Humphrey Milford, Oxford University Press, with an introduction and appendix by Thomas William Rolleston.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] It was published by Charles Ollier in July 1821 (see 1821 in poetry) with a preface in which Shelley made the mistaken assertion that Keats had died from a rupture of the lung induced by rage at the unfairly harsh reviews of his verse in the *Quarterly Review* and other journals.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He also thanked Joseph Severn for caring for Keats in Rome.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] This praise increased literary interest in Severn's works.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Shelley was introduced to Keats in Hampstead towards the end of 1816 by their mutual friend, Leigh Hunt, who was to transfer his enthusiasm from Keats to Shelley.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Shelley's initial admiration of Keats was ambiguous: his reception to Keats' *Endymion* was largely unfavourable, while he found his later work, *Hyperion*, to be the highest example of contemporary poetry.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Keats found some of Shelley's advice patronising (the suggestion, for example, that Keats should not publish his early work).
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] It is also possible that Keats resented Hunt's transferred allegiance.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Despite this, the two poets exchanged letters after Shelley and his wife moved to Italy.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] When Keats fell ill, the Shelleys invited him to stay with them in Pisa, but Keats only made it as far as Rome, accompanied by the painter Severn.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Shelley's concern for Keats's health remained undimmed, until he learned months after the fact that Keats had died in Rome, prompting the composition of *Adonais*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Shelley regarded *Adonais* as the "least imperfect" of his works.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The poet weeps for John Keats, who is dead and who will be long mourned.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He calls on Urania to mourn for Keats who died in Rome (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The poet summons the subject matter of Keats's poetry to weep for him.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] It comes and mourns at his bidding (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Nature, celebrated by Keats in his poetry, mourns him.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Spring, which brings nature to new life, cannot restore him (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Urania rises, goes to Keats's death chamber and laments that she cannot join him in death (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Fellow poets mourn the death of Keats: Byron, Thomas Moore, Shelley, and Leigh Hunt (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The anonymous *Quarterly Review* critic is blamed for Keats's death and chastised (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The poet urges the mourners not to weep any longer.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Keats has become a portion of the eternal and is free from the attacks of reviewers.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He is not dead; it is the living who are dead.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He has gone where "envy and calumny and hate and pain" cannot reach him.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He is "made one with Nature." His being has been withdrawn into the one Spirit which is responsible for all beauty.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In eternity, other poets, among them Thomas Chatterton, Sir Philip Sidney, and the Roman poet Lucan, come to greet him (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Let anyone who still mourns Keats send his "spirit's light" beyond space and be filled with hope, or let him go to Rome where Keats is buried.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Let him "Seek shelter in the shadow of the tomb. / What Adonais is, why fear we to become?" He is with the unchanging Spirit, Intellectual Beauty, or Love in heaven.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] By comparison with the clear light of eternity, life is a stain (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The poet tells himself he should now depart from life, which has nothing left to offer.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The One, which is Light, Beauty, Benediction, and Love, now shines on him.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He feels carried "darkly, fearfully, afar" to where the soul of Keats glows like a star, in the dwelling where those who will live forever are (sts.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The over-riding theme is one of despair.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Mourners are implored to "weep for Adonais—he is dead!" In Stanza 9 the "flocks" of the deceased appear, representing his dreams and inspirations.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In Stanza 13, the personifications of the thoughts, emotions, attitudes, and skills of the deceased appear.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In Stanza 22, Urania is awakened by the grief of Misery and the poet.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The lament is invoked: "He will awake no more, oh, never more!" Urania pleads in vain for Adonais to awake and to arise.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In Stanzas 30 through 34, a series of human mourners appears.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The "Pilgrim of Eternity" is Lord Byron, George Gordon, who had met and was a friend of Shelley's but who had never met Keats.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The Irish poet Thomas Moore then appears who laments the sadness and loss that time causes.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Shelley himself and Leigh Hunt are also part of the "procession of mourners".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In Stanzas 31 through 34 the mourner is described as "one frail Form" who has "fled astray", "his branded and ensanguined brow" a brow "like Cain's or Christ's".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The sense of despair and hopelessness continues.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Keats transcends human life and has been unified with the immortal: "He has outsoared the shadow of our night;/Envy and calumny and hate and pain,/ ...
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Can touch him not and torture not again....
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] He is made one with Nature." Keats is as one with Nature, the Power, the One, and the one Spirit.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Adonais "is not dead, he doth not sleep, he hath awaken'd from the dream of life." "Who mourns for Adonais?" he asks in stanza 47.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] "What Adonais is, why fear we to become?" he asks in stanza 51.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] It is life's worldly cares—that obscuring and distracting "dome of many-coloured glass"—not Death that is the enemy and the source of human despair.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The section on Rome (stanzas 48–52) is significant in the poem not only because Keats and Shelley's son are buried in the Protestant cemetery there but also because the section offers an alternative way of understanding themes already expressed in the poem.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Beginning with a statement of alternativeness ("Or go to Rome"), the section provides an alternative way for the continuing mourner to imagine Adonais as part of the World Soul and so cease mourning.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] This latter concept is embodied in the idea of Rome as the "Eternal" city.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] In addition, the description of Keats's spirit as part of "Eternal" Rome shows parallels with the earlier description, in stanzas 44–46, of his spirit becoming part of the "firmament" of eternal stars which are the immortal spirits of great poets.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] And in stanza 52, as "The One" is to the "many" and "heaven's light" is to "Earth's shadows" and the "white radiance of Eternity" is to multicolored Life, so "The glory" of the World Soul is to aspects of Rome that represent death but symbolise eternity.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] By means of these parallels, the Rome section becomes fully integrated into the poem.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Mick Jagger of the Rolling Stones read a part of *Adonais* at the Brian Jones concert at London's Hyde Park on 5 July 1969.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Jones, founder and guitarist of the Stones, had drowned 3 July 1969 in his swimming pool.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] Actor Vincent Price read *Adonais* on a Caedmon Records recording which was released, originally in 1956, as an LP record and a cassette recording, Caedmon CPN 1059 and TC 1059.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] The English rock band The Cure has recorded a song entitled "Adonais" based on the Shelley elegy as a B-side single and on the collection *Join the Dots: B-Sides and Rarities, 1978–2001* (2004).
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/adonaïs] "Adonais" was originally the B-side to "The 13th", released in 1996.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] It is a blank-verse tale recounting an idealistic poet’s search for perfect love and knowledge.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] It explores the themes of idealism versus realism and the futility of abstractions devoid of human connection.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The narrator relates how a young and visionary poet abandons society and travels to unexplored and desolate regions in the Caucasus and Arabia in quest of a perfect or ideal love, a "veiled maid" which he sees in a dream.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] "Alastor" is an avenging spirit that punishes narcissism and self-centered intellectual obsessions that displace "sweet human love" and society.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Nature mirrors the poet's inner thoughts and emotions which begin as redolent and vibrant but turn barren and desolate.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The poet ultimately rejects human connection, represented by the "Arab maiden", instead pursuing his ideal or abstract dream or vision.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] His quest ends tragically as he dies in solitude and isolation.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Peacock suggested the name Alastor, which comes from Roman mythology.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Peacock has defined Alastor as "evil genius".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The name does not refer to the hero or Poet of the poem, however, but instead to the spirit who divinely animates the Poet's imagination.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The Poet rejects an "Arab maiden" in his search for an idealised embodiment of a woman.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] As the Poet wanders one night, he dreams of a "veiled maid" whose "voice was like the voice of his own soul." This veiled vision brings with her an intimation of the supernatural world that lies beyond nature.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] This dream vision serves as a mediator between the natural and supernatural domains by being both spirit and an element of human love.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] He saw "awful ruins of the days of old", Athens, Tyre, Balbec, Jerusalem, "the fallen towers of Babylon", "the eternal pyramids", Memphis, and Thebes.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The thrilling secrets of the birth of time.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Once touched by the maddening hand of the supernatural, the Poet restlessly searches for a reconciliation with his lost vision.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Though his imagination craves a reunion with the infinite, it too is ultimately anchored to the perceptions of the natural world.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Ruminating on thoughts of death as the possible next step beyond dream to the supernatural world he tasted, the Poet notices a small boat ("little shallop") floating down a nearby river.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Passively, he sits in the boat furiously being driven down the river by a smooth wave.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Deeper and deeper into the very source of the natural world he rushes.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Like the water's surface supports the boat, the supernatural world "cradles" the mutability both of nature and of man.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] As his senses are literally dulled, his imagination helps him sense the spirit's supernatural presence.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Instead of perceiving the vision through the senses, the Poet imaginatively observes her in the dying images of the passing objects of nature.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The boat flows onward to an "immeasurable void" and the Poet finds himself ready to sink into the supernatural world and break through the threshold into death.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] When the Poet reaches the "obscurest chasm" his last sight is of the moon.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] As that image fades from the Poet's mind, he has finally attained transcendence to the supernatural world.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The journey to the very source of nature led, finally, to an immanence within nature's very structure and to a world free of decay and change.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The work was first published in London in 1816 (see 1816 in poetry) under the title *Alastor; or, The Spirit of Solitude: And Other Poems*, printed for Baldwin, Cradock and Joy, Pater-Noster Row; and Carpenter and Son, Old Bond-Street: by S.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Shelley also quotes from William Wordsworth's *The Excursion* (1814) the lines, "The good die first,/ And they whose hearts are dry as summer dust / Burn to the socket!" The line "It is a woe 'too deep for tears'" is a quote from Wordsworth's "Ode: Intimations of Immortality".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Reviews were initially negative when *Alastor* was published in 1816.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] John Gibson Lockhart of *Blackwood's Edinburgh Magazine* wrote the first major positive review in the November 1819 issue.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Lockhart wrote that Shelley is "a man of genius...
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Leigh Hunt praised *Alastor* in the December 1816 issue of *The Examiner*.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The poem was attacked by contemporary critics for its "obscurity".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] In a review in *The Monthly Review* for April 1816, the critic wrote: "We must candidly own that these poems are beyond our comprehension; and we did not obtain a clue to their sublime obscurity, till an address to Mr.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Mary Shelley, in her note on the work, wrote: "None of Shelley's poems is more characteristic than this." In the spring of 1815, Shelley had been erroneously diagnosed as suffering from consumption.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Shelley suffered from spasms and there were abscesses in his lungs.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] He made a full recovery but the shock of imminent death is reflected in the work.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Critics have spent a great deal of effort attempting to identify the Poet.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] One possibility is William Wordsworth, since the poem is framed with direct quotations from Wordsworth's poetry, and Shelley had a deeply ambivalent reaction to Wordsworth's poetry, as witnessed in his sonnet "To Wordsworth".
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Another is Robert Southey, whom Shelley had much admired and whose *Thalaba the Destroyer*, a favourite poem of Shelley's, prefigures *Alastor* in imagery and quest-narrative.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Shelley sent a copy of the book to Southey.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] Similarities in imagery to Samuel Taylor Coleridge's *Kubla Khan* have been noted but Shelley is unlikely to have read that poem, still unpublished at the time of *Alastor*'s composition.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] The similarities might be explained by those between *Thalaba* and *Kubla Khan*, each of which was partly composed while Southey and Coleridge were in close contact.
[src:a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough/alastor-or-the-spirit-of-solitude] In 1912, Russian composer Nikolai Myaskovsky wrote his symphonic poem *Alastor, Poème d'après Shelley* (Op.
